This is becoming a really interesting problem -- Democrats are ahead in the generic House polling by about 7 points, which should make them more likely than not to take back control, according to Sam Wang's polling chart. And yet, a 30 seat deficit is a large undertaking and the qualitative prognosticators are bearish that they can take it back. Rothenberg and Gonzales think 219 seats are safe for Republicans, essentially giving the Democrats close to a 0% chance of taking the House. Cook Political has 202 solid seats for Republicans with another 23 as lean/likely for them -- more uncertainty but still very favorable to Republicans.
Even if the Democrats win every district that Obama won in the 2012 election, they would still need more. The odds are definitely stacked against them.

At least 3 factors make Dem control extremely unlikely. 1) Republicans have their largest House majority (+59 seats) since 1928, so the "margin of safety" for Republican control is very large. 2) Democrats are more concentrated in urban areas than they've ever been before, creating a natural geographic impediment for Democrats to pick up seats. 3) District gerrymandering following the massive Republican wins in state legislatures in 2010 have created even larger structural advantages for Republicans seeking House seats.

Ticket-splitting has gone out of fashion in recent elections. It should enjoy a resurgence this year. Republicans who cannot stomach Donald Trump have the option of voting Libertarian for President. A few may even vote for Sec. Clinton. In either case, keeping the House, specifically, firmly in Republican hands (however dysfunctional) will be the preferred down-ticket result. Add in Voter ID laws in states where Sec. Clinton might otherwise be able to flip a House seat or two, and you're looking at a majority that may be smaller, but won't be toppled. This election is about fear, not about hope. Younger voters-- who could sweep in a new majority if present in number-- are not motivated by fear. Older voters-- who will be voting in number-- are.

Taking a different framework to the question from the Senate question due to the number of seats in contention, even at this early stage. Baseline: only 3 out of 17 presidential election years (http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Research/Files/Reports/2013/07/vital-statistics-congress-mann-ornstein/Vital-Statistics-Chapter-2--Congressional-Elections.pdf?la=en) have seen a swing in house of more than 30 seats (the number needed for Democrats to hit 218): 18% (low baseline, but given the last time it happened was in 1980 when Reagan beat Carter, one could easily argue the baseline should be even lower). Normally I would probably leave it there but the 1964 occasion when it did happen has enough similarities (improving economy, semi-incumbent Democrat, Republican candidate with unpopular conservative views) that I am going to bump the baseline by 10%, as a first shift, on the basis that a Trump/Cruz candidacy will mobilise a larger democrat turnout.
As much as Republicans tend to mobilize themselves better than Democrats, young voters have been uncharacteristically active in this election cycle, and I expect this to sway the results.

Most House seats are "safe seats" for one party or the other. If you look at individual districts, you can see how this works. Members of Congress are rated on their votes by numerous special interest groups. It turns out that you can't get elected to the House in very many places by taking a middle road. You have to line up on one end of the political spectrum, or the other. You need to have high ratings from the watchdog groups that focus on issues that are important in your district. State Legislatures have supported this game by gerrymandering most of the districts in the country. This makes things convenient for fund raising and vote getting. Senators run state-wide, but House members run district-by-district, Sure, trouble in the Presidential race can have an impact down ballot. But if you vote in a typical House district, it would be very difficult for you to give up on every special interest issue that has been near and dear to your heart. Chances are, your representative has earned top roll call scores from all of your favorite special interest groups. He or she has been proven to vote the way you think. You're not going to vote for someone else. This is what makes it so difficult to shift a majority in the House.

There's not a good way to quantify this without doing a lot more state-by-state research, so I guess I mostly just looked at how often a margin like this has been overcome before (twice in the last 20 congresses, 112th and 104th), both of them from Democratic to Republican. Dem takeovers have seemed more gradual? But with a somewhat confused Republican identity right now, the odds might bump a bit higher than one in ten. At least that's what I think so far, without diving too deeply into it.

The holders of House seats are overwhelmingly determined by state houses, during redistricting. Republicans were in a particularly good position to claim/protect those seats after the 2010 census, as they held majorities in more state legislatures than the Democrats did. Roll Call's 2016 election map (http://media.cq.com/raceratings/) shows 219 of 247 current Republican seats as "safe," with 7 "leaning," 5 "favored" and 3 "tilting." Only 11 are "toss-ups." The safe seats, alone, ensure the majority. And their holders will, without question, all be campaigning against the Democratic presidential nominee (which contender makes little difference), who will "fire up the base" much more thoroughly than even Donald Trump is likely to do for the Democrats. This may not work in the Senate, but that house is beyond the scope of this question.
